"Davis J.L., Mitrovica J.X.","Glacial isostatic adjustment and the anomalous tide gauge record of eastern North America",1996,"Nature","379","6563",,"331","333",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0029769591&partnerID=40&md5=354795de6a7556b49b3a8bbd863ba379","Harvard-Smithsonian Ctr. Astrophys., 60 Garden Street, Cambridge, MA 02138, United States; Department of Physics, University of Toronto, 60 St George Street, Toronto, Ont. M5S 1A7, Canada","Davis, J.L., Harvard-Smithsonian Ctr. Astrophys., 60 Garden Street, Cambridge, MA 02138, United States; Mitrovica, J.X., Department of Physics, University of Toronto, 60 St George Street, Toronto, Ont. M5S 1A7, Canada","SEA-LEVEL variations, as recorded by the global network of tide gauges, represent a rich data set for studying a wide range of natural and anthropogenic phenomena, such as the sea-level rise induced by possible global warming. For this purpose, long-term sea-level trends must be corrected for the 'contaminating' effects of continuing glacial isostatic adjustment1-5 (GIA). The numerical correction procedure has, for sites on the east coast of North America, yielded a set of highly anomalous sea-level rates characterized by systematic geographical trends2,4,5. We demonstrate that these trends are a consequence of inadequacies in the previous 'standard' numerical prediction for GIA. In particular, we find that the well-known trends in the GIA-corrected tide gauge rates are eliminated if the lower-mantle viscosity of the Earth model used in the GIA prediction is increased. This result obviates the need to explain the anomalous trend as a manifestation of Gulf Stream ocean circulation4 or neotectonic processes2.",,"anomalous records; glacial isostasy; glacial isostatic adjustment; isostasy; sea level trend; sea level variations; tide gauge; North America; North America, Atlantic Coast",,,,,,"Peltier, W.R., Tushingham, A.M., (1989) Science, 244, pp. 806-810; Gornitz, V., Seeber, L., (1990) Tectonophysics, 178, pp. 127-150; Peltier, W.R., Tushingham, A.M., (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 6779-6796; Douglas, B.C., (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 6981-6992; Trupin, A.S., Wahr, J.M., (1991) Globel Isostasy, Sea Level, and Mantle Rheology, pp. 271-284. , (eds Sabadini, R. & Lambeck, K.) Kluwer, Dordrecht; Tushingham, A.M., Pelter, W.R., (1992) J. Geophys. Res., 97, pp. 3285-3304; Dziewonski, A.M., Anderson, D.L., (1981) Phys. Earth Planet. Inter., 25, pp. 297-366; Tushingham, A.M., Peltier, W.R., (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 4497-4523; Mitrovica, J.X., Pettier, W.R., (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 20053-20071; Cathles, L.M., (1975) The Viscosity of the Earth's Mantle, , Princeton Univ, press; Pettier, W.R., Andrews, J.T., (1976) Geophys. J. R. Astr. Soc., 46, pp. 606-646; Wu, P., Peltier, W.R., (1983) Geophys. J. R. Astr. Soc., 74, pp. 377-450; Mrtrovica, J.X., Davis, J.L., Shapiro, I.I., (1994) J. Geophys. Res., 99, pp. 7075-7102; Maul, G.A., Martin, D.M., (1993) Geophys. Res. Lett., 20, pp. 1955-1958; Gornitz, V., Lebedeff, S., Hansen, J., (1982) Science, 215, pp. 1611-1614; Braatz, B.V., Aubrey, D.G., (1987) Sea-Level Fluctuation and Coastal Evolution, pp. 29-46. , (eds Nummedal, D , Pilkey, O H & Howard, J D.) Spec Publ. 41, Soc. Econ. Paleontol Mineral., Tulsa, OK; Uchupi, E., Aubrey, D.G., (1988) J. Geol., 95, pp. 79-80; Prowell, D.C., (1988) The Atlantic Continental Margin, pp. 557-564. , (eds Shendan, R. E. & Grow, J. A.) Geol. Soc Am., Boulder, CO; Lambeck, K., Johnston, P., Nakada, M., (1990) Geophys J. Int., 103, pp. 451-468; Mitrovica, J.X., Peltier, W.R., (1995) Geophys. J. Int., 122, pp. 353-377; Denton, H.H., Hughes, I.J., (1981) The Last Great Ice Sheets, , Wiley, New York; Sabadini, R., Yuen, D.A., Portney, M., (1986) Geophys. Res. Lett., 13, pp. 337-340; Gaspenni, P., Sabadini, R., (1989) Geophys J. Int, 98, pp. 413-428; Manga, M., O'Connell, R.J., (1995) Geophys Res Lett., 22, pp. 1949-1952; Breuer, A., Wolf, D., (1995) Geophys. J. Int